After August 1977, each bank, depending on its holdings of selected asset items, was allocated a certain quota of the total borrowings permitted at the Bank Rate. Borrowings in excess of this quota were subjected to a penal rate of interest of 15 per cent per annum. In September 1979, a graduated scale of penal rates ranging between 15 per cent and 25 per cent was introduced. It was further revised upward to a range of 20 per cent to 30 per cent, with effect from April 1960. With effect from August 1980, the Bank Rate was raised to 14 per cent, while the penai rate was raised to a range 21-30 per cent tn March 1983, the Bank Rate was brought down to 13 per cent and the penal rate was fixed at 20 per cent. With effect from 23 November 1983, the practice of granting advances to commercial banks under a penal rate was discontinued. With effect from 30 December 1985, the Central Bank reduced the lending rate on its advances to 11 per cent. A further reduction, to 10 per cent, was made with effect from 07 August 1987. The Central Bank increased the lending rate on advances to 14 per cent wiih effect from 15 June 1989. The rate was increased again to 15 per cent, with effect from 06 July 1990 and to 17 per cent with effect from 04 January 1991. This rate was brought down to 16 per cent with effect from 13 August 1999. This rate was increased to 18 per cent with effect from 2 October 2000 and again to 20 per cent and 25 per cent with effect from 08 November 2000 and 21 November 2000. (c) 3-month Treasury bills were not offered to the market at the auctions on 22 September, 29 September and 06 October 1999 in order to reduce the amount of bills maturing towards the end of December 1999 as a precautionary measure to address a possible shortage in market liquidity arising from the Y2K issue. (d) A new day count formula for Treasury bills based on international norms, was introduced with effect from 20 October 1999. Accordingly, Treasury bills are issued with 91-days, 182-days and 364-days of day counts to maturity instead of 3-month, 6-month and 12-month Treasury bills issued upto 20th October 1999.
